<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOLYFIELD, MOORER WEIGH 214 FOR RARE EQUAL-SIZE MATCHUP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TIM KAWAKAMI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Evander Holyfield and Michael Moorer, two 6-foot-2 boxers accustomed to 
fighting taller, heavier opponents, each weighed in at 214 pounds Wednesday, 
two days before their heavyweight championship fight at Caesars Palace. 
</P>
<P>
 Holyfield's last four opponents have weighed-in at an average of 235 1/2 
pounds and, in his most recent fight, Holyfield weighed in 34 pounds lighter 
than 6-5, 246-pound Riddick Bowe. 
</P>
<P>
 Holyfield and Moorer came up from lighter divisions into heavyweight 
prominence, which Holyfield says shows they both can succeed despite a size 
disadvantage. 
</P>
<P>
 "We both know that it isn't size or height that makes a difference," Holyfield 
said. "When you go into the ring with two people with that mentality, it's 
going to be an explosive fight." TIM KAWAKAMI 
</P>
</TEXT>
