<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES; REPAIR OF 
QUAKE-DAMAGED COLISEUM PERISTYLE STUDIED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A discussion on repair of the quake-damaged peristyle end of the Los Angeles 
Memorial Coliseum was held Wednesday by representatives of the Coliseum, state 
historic preservation groups and officials of the Federal Emergency Management 
Agency. Demolition and reconstruction of some of the historic columns was one 
option examined. 
</P>
<P>
 The Coliseum's project director, Don C. Webb, said that under all three 
options for repair that are being considered, the central arch of the peristyle 
would remain. But side columns may be rebuilt, he said, and all parts of the 
peristyle structure will have to be reinforced or crowned with new material, at 
the minimum. 
</P>
<P>
 No cost estimates have been made for this part of the Coliseum repair. Such 
work is apt to be unfinished in time for next fall's football season, Webb 
said, even while other parts of the stadium are opened to spectators. Other 
repair costs have been estimated at $34.7 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
