<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: HUNTINGTON BEACH; CITY TO GIVE $4,000 FOR GRAD NITE 
PARTIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL BILLITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 To foster sane-and-sober Grad Nite parties for local students, the city is 
donating $1,000 to each festivity at its four public high schools. 
</P>
<P>
 The City Council unanimously voted Monday to make the gifts to the Grad Nite 
celebrations at Huntington Beach, Marina, Edison and Ocean View high schools. 
</P>
<P>
 Most county high schools hold Grad Nite parties on the evening of high school 
graduation. The events, supervised by parents and faculty, are usually held on 
campus and feature an array of entertainment and prizes. 
</P>
<P>
 Supporters of Grad Nite, including the Huntington Beach Police Department, 
contend that the high school graduates are kept safe at the alcohol- and 
drug-free events. 
</P>
<P>
 The city's $4,000 donation to the Grad Nite parties comes from the Police 
Department's Narcotic Asset Forfeiture Fund. That fund consists of money and 
property seized from drug dealers. BILL BILLITER 
</P>
</TEXT>
