<P>
GLOBAL MARKETS AND ECONOMIC UPDATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 MEXICAN STOCKS 
</P>
<P>
 * The Bolsa crashed again Wednesday, falling 107.44 points, or 5.2%, to 
1,957.33 -- its lowest close since Nov. 8. The catalyst was a surge in 
short-term interest rates, as Mexico's central bank allowed rates to rise to 
18% to defend the peso. 
</P>
<P>
 * The market has been reeling for months from the slowing economy and from the 
political aftermath of presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio's 
assassination. Now, with U.S. interest rates continuing to rise, Mexico has 
little choice but to boost domestic rates to keep capital from fleeing. But in 
the near term, that may further depress stock prices, despite their already low 
price-to-earnings ratios, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
 Source: D.A. Campbell; Times wire services SPOTLIGHT: THE NETHERLANDS 
</P>
<P>
 The recession in Western Europe has slowed the growth of the Dutch economy, 
which is dependent on trade. Recently, the government has been working to get 
more foreign investment from outside of Europe. The nation has traditionally 
been a gateway to European markets for overseas goods. 
</P>
<P>
 Sources: Bank of America; World Information Services 
</P>
