<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: ELECTIONS; CARSON; CITY PONDERS BEST WAY TO FILL COUNCIL SEAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY GUTHRIE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Residents packed the City Council chambers Tuesday to see Michael I. Mitoma 
sworn in as the city's first directly elected mayor.  
</P>
<P>
 Councilman Peter D. Fajardo was unanimously reelected mayor pro tem. The 
council also said farewell to Councilwoman Sylvia L. Muise-Perez, whose term 
expired this year. 
</P>
<P>
 With Mitoma leaving his council seat to become mayor, the City Council now has 
only four members. The council has 30 days to decide whether to appoint someone 
to fill the vacancy or hold another election. 
</P>
<P>
 Because ethnicity became an issue in the campaign between Mitoma, a Japanese 
American, and James H. Peoples, an African American, the council has felt some 
pressure to appoint a black person to fill the position.  
</P>
<P>
 Mitoma said he favors appointment because it would save the city money and 
staff time. Although he said he does not have a candidate in mind, his main 
criterion for selection is public service. 
</P>
<P>
 "I will never appoint somebody (who) has never done anything for the 
community," Mitoma said. "I don't give a darn whether they are black or purple. 
They have to have served the community." 
</P>
<P>
 Keith McDonald, an African American who came in second in a race for the open 
council seat in the April 12 election, said he thinks residents are tired of 
the divisiveness that comes with elections. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think we need some type of cooling period," McDonald said. He acknowledged 
that he would like to be appointed to the seat but said it is important that 
the council member represent more than just one part of the city. 
</P>
<P>
 "They can't appoint just for color. . . . The council members are going to 
have to step up to the plate and show leadership," McDonald said. "I think that 
all the communities and all areas of the city need to feel that they are 
represented." 
</P>
<P>
 City Clerk Helen Kawagoe said the city could hold an election that would 
coincide with the statewide elections Nov. 8. She estimated that adding the 
council election to that ballot would cost the city about $15,000. MARY GUTHRIE 
</P>
</TEXT>
